         <abstract>
            <p>The author analyzes corporate tender offers in the period 1968-72 and contrasts those with tender offers in the period 1956-67. Shifting trends in cash versus exchange tender offers, the significant different levels of premiums, dwindling success rates of tender offers, and changing financial characteristics of the firms under attack are highlighted. Target corporations are analyzed as to profitability, return on invested capital, asset size, and liquidity. In conclusion, the author indicates ways in which the financial manager may perfect a tender offer or defend against such a tender offer.</p>
